tle> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=nukepulse>NukePulse</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NEP Freighter Crewman</span><br>  Posts: 77<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(6/27/03 3:51 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=341.topic>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   19th Century 'Helios' style pulse driven space craft </span><hr size=1> The 19th Century German engineer <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>'Hermann Ganswindt'</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->did indeed envision a pulse unit driven space craft. Tim1965  reworked the design into an external pulse craft while Herman actually proposed a craft that used pulse units that were to be detonated inside of 2 to 4  very long ‘thrust tubes’. Essentially the machine was supposed to kick itself to the moon by rapidly detonating huge dynamite powered shotgun shells inside of its thrust tubes. Yes that’s right the pulse units were designed to send  clouds of high velocity steel balls out the rear end of the craft to provide the required thrust.<br>
<br>
Basically the ships configuration was a bullet shaped crew compartment on the forward end to which were attached 4 long thrust tubes. To the rear of the crew compartment were the charge magazines that held the ‘shotgun shells’. Although no specific details of the ships internals were given one can imagine some very interesting 19th century engineering solutions. I would really love to see a cutaway of the machine and take a look at how the designer intended to extract pulse units from the magazines and then send them up to the firing room to be loaded into the breeches of the thrust tubes and  fired. I wonder what kind of pulse unit firing rate Herman envisioned?<br>
<br>
While I don’t think that the machine is at all practical I agree with DustysLaunchPad that this 19th century idea was truly amazing and showed the power of the human imagination. <br>
<br>
I have tossed together a 3D model of what the ship looked like but I am working from the memory of an image I saw in a book by  Herman Oberth when I was a kid. The image I have created is correct in all the major details but I sure wish I could find the lithographed image I remember seeing in that book.<br>
<br>
Since I can’t crosspost to this board from Geocities you will have to enter the images URL in your browser to look at the image if you are interested. <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE FONT START--><span style="color:orange;font-size:small;"><!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>PICTURE---(www.geocities.com/CapeCanaveral/Galaxy/9585/hermang.jpg)---PICTURE</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--></span><!--EZCODE FONT END-->NukePulse<br>
 <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=nukepulse>NukePulse</A> at: 6/27/03 8:55 am<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=atomicconspiracy>Atomic Conspiracy</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Moderator</span><br>  Posts: 261<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(6/27/03 7:13 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=341.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: 19th Century 'Helios' style pulse driven space craft </span><hr size=1> Good image. The inventor was <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.spacefame.org/ganswindt.html">Hermann Gandswindt</a><!--EZCODE LINK END-->, mistakenly referred to as Hans Gandtswindt in a number of references. <br>
FAS even has a reference to him in its article on the <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.fas.org/spp/eprint/origins/part06.htm">Beginnings of Spaceflight</a><!--EZCODE LINK END-->.<br>
Wernher von Braun mentions him in his article on <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.meaus.com/spaceProphet.html">Hermann von Oberth</a><!--EZCODE LINK END-->. <br>
<br>
Gandswindt obviously had a limited understanding of reaction propulsion, no surprise in 1891, or he would not have proposed using steel balls in the reaction mass. It would be far better to replace them with that much more dynamite.<br>
<br>
According to <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www0.arch.cuhk.edu.hk/~hall/ag/Dissertation/1_2.htm">Theodore Hall's</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--> 1994 doctoral dissertation Gandswindt had a workable idea for artificial gravity, and we can even credit him with inventing the shock-mounted crew compartment, though his was upside down relative to that of Orion:  <br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr> Hermann Ganswindt, a contemporary of Tsiolkovsky, independently developed circa 1890 a concept for a space ship that incorporated reaction propulsion and artificial gravity.  His mathematical skills were not as well developed as Tsiolkovsky's, and this limited his ability to either apply or contribute useful theories.<br>
<br>
The crew compartment of Ganswindt's ship was to be a horizontal cylinder <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong><!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>suspended by shock-absorbing springs below the engine assembly</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--></strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->.  An exhaust well was to be cut cross-wise through the center of this cylinder to allow the passage of spent steel shells from the explosion chamber above.  (Ganswindt did not believe that mere gaseous exhaust could produce sufficient reaction thrust.)  Ganswindt understood that the crew would experience weightlessness when the engine was shut off, and proposed to provide artificial gravity by rotating the vehicle around the exhaust well, so that the ends of the crew cylinder would become floors.  Apparently, this scheme was never worked out in detail.<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>(Emphasis added)</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--> <br>
<br>
One of Hall's sources is the classic reference, <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>History of Rocketry and Space Travel</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> by Fred Ordway and Wernher von Braun. This mentions a similar and earlier proposal by one Nikolai Kibalchich (pg. 40). This called for propelling a platform by feeding gunpowder cartridges into a chamber, and changing the direction of the chamber's axis to change the vehicle's flightpath. To the best of my knowledge, this is the first proposal for vectored thrust control. <br>
Interestingly enough, Kibalchich wrote this proposal while he was in prison awaiting execution for his part in the 1881 assassination of Czar Alexander II. The latter was killed by a bomb, so Kibalchich apparently knew something about explosives in a practical sense. His notes were not published until 1918.<br>
<br>
By 1891, the basic technology of machine guns was well advanced, and this could have been adapted to Gandswindt's proposal as a way of feeding the cartridges rapidly into the chambers. A kind of low velocity Gatling gun, driven by electric motors or compressed air, could have done it; and Maxim gun principles could also have been applied by then. Given better engineering and financial support than Gandswindt could manage by himself, this might have led to a controllable flying machine of some kind, but not to outer space.  <br>
